<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE gxl SYSTEM "http://ginsim.org/GINML_2_2.dtd">
<gxl xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">
  <graph class="regulatory" id="RA_APL_model_19Nov2024" nodeorder="RA PML_RARAg PLZF_RARAg RARA PML PML_RARA PLZF PLZF_RARA USP37 CoAct_COMP EZH2 PRC2 CoRep_COMP CDKN1A CDKN1B CDKN2D RB1 TP53 SKP2 MDM2 CAK CCNA2 CCND1 CCNE2 CDK4_6 CDK2 E2F1 MYC DUSP6 POU2F1 GATA2 RUNX1 SPI1 CEBPAB CEBPE RARB">
    <nodestyle background="#ffffff" foreground="#000000" text="#000000" shape="RECTANGLE" width="120" height="45"/>
    <nodestyle name="Input" background="#99ffff" text="#000000" width="125"/>
    <nodestyle name="Arrest" background="#ff9999"/>
    <nodestyle name="Differentiation" background="#ffff33"/>
    <nodestyle name="Proliferation" background="#99ff99"/>
    <nodestyle name="Epigenetic" background="#ffcc33" height="45"/>
    <edgestyle color="#000000" pattern="SIMPLE" line_width="3" properties="positive:#00c800 negative:#c80000 dual:#0000c8"/>
    <edgestyle name="Edge style" pattern="DASH"/>
    <node id="RA" name="Retinoic Acid" maxvalue="2" input="true">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=CHEBI:15367"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32359642/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23841729/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>RA node represents the Retinoic Acid molecule [1].
It has hormonal effects inducing differentiation on hematopoietic cells, which is mediated mostly by the transcriptional activation of receptors complexes (RAR/RXR) bound to the Retinoic Acid Receptor Elements (RARE) in specific genes [2]. The All Trans Retinoic Acid is used as a therapeutic agent, usually in combination with chemotherapy or arsenic trioxide (ATO) to treat Acute Promyelocytic Leukaemia [3].
It is the only multilevel node in the network. 
Considered as an input, its initial level is maintained during each simulation, corresponding to:
Level 2 -&gt; Pharmacological RA concentration (μM range)
Level 1 -&gt; Physiological RA concentration (nM range)
Level 0 -&gt; No or negligible RA</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="918" y="63" style="Input"/>
    </node>
    <node id="PML_RARAg" name="PML::RARA fusion gene" maxvalue="1" input="true">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2170850/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20159610/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23841729/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>PML_RARAg node represents the fusion gene that results from the aberrant translocation t(15;17) involving the promyelocytic leukemia (PML) gene and the retinoic acid receptor alpha (RARA) gene [1]. It interferes with the normal RARA signalling and blocks myeloid differentiation leading to the accumulation of promyelocytes [2]. This fusion is associated with a form of Acute Promyelocytic Leukaemia which is primarily sensitive and responsive to the Retinoic Acid treatment in combination with chemotherapy or arsenic trioxide [3].
It is an input node denoting the presence of the fusion gene.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="537" y="41" style="Input"/>
    </node>
    <node id="PLZF_RARAg" name="PLZF::RARA fusion gene" maxvalue="1" input="true">
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8302850/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9462740/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9531570/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>PLZF_RARAg node represents the fusion gene that results from the aberrant translocation t(11;17) involving the promyelocytic leukemia zinc finger (PLZF) gene and the retinoic acid receptor alpha (RARA) gene [1]. It interferes with the normal RARA signalling and blocks myeloid differentiation leading to the accumulation of promyelocytes. This fusion is associated with a form of Acute Promyelocytic Leukaemia which is primarily resistant to the Retinoic Acid treatment [2, 3].
It is an input node denoting the presence of the fusion gene.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1231" y="37" style="Input"/>
    </node>
    <node id="RARA" name="Retinoic Acid Receptor" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:9864"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20970498/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>RARA node represents the Retinoic Acid Receptor protein subunit [1].
It forms heterodimers with RXR subunits and bind to the RARE of specific genes. In the absence of RA the complex recruits co-repressors such as SMRT, NCOR1 and PRC2 to silence targets genes. Upon RA binding, co-activators such as NCOA1 and RAC3 are recruited, and the transcription of the target genes is enabled [2].
Its basal value is set to 1 per default.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1069" y="126" style="Differentiation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="PML" name="PML nuclear body scaffold" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!CDK2"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:9113"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21840486/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23526763/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17562868/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>PML node represents the PML nuclear body scaffold [1].
It is located in nuclear bodies and functions as a transcription factor and tumor suppressor. It is involved in cell cycle regulation [2, 3].
It is the translocation partner involved in the PML::RARA APL variant, which is sensitive to RA therapy [4].
Its basal value is set to 1 per default.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="245" y="145" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="PML_RARA" name="PML::RARA fusion protein" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="PML_RARAg &amp; CAK"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2170850/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20159610/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23841729/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>PML_RARA node represents the fusion protein that results from the aberrant translocation t(15;17) involving the promyelocytic leukemia (PML) gene and the retinoic acid receptor alpha (RARA) gene [1]. It interferes with the normal RARA signalling and blocks myeloid differentiation leading to the accumulation of promyelocytes [2]. This fusion is associated with a form of Acute Promyelocytic Leukaemia which is primarily sensitive and responsive to the Retinoic Acid treatment in combination with chemotherapy or arsenic trioxide [3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="538" y="193" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="PLZF" name="Zinc finger and BTB domain containing 16" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="GATA2 &amp; !CDK2"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:12930"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8622986/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14645547/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18246121/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>PLZF node represents the protein Zinc finger and BTB domain containing 16, also named PLZF, involved in cell cycle regulation  [1].
It is the translocation partner involved in the PLZF::RARA APL variant, which is resistant to pharmacological doses of RA [2].
It represses MYC expression [3], and is inhibited by Cyclin Dependent Kinase 2 (CDK2) [4].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1441" y="261" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="PLZF_RARA" name="PLZF::RARA fusion protein" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="PLZF_RARAg &amp; USP37 &amp; CAK"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8302850/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9462740/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9531570/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>PLZF_RARA node represents the fusion protein that results from the aberrant translocation t(11;17) involving the promyelocytic leukemia zinc finger (PLZF) gene and the retinoic acid receptor alpha (RARA) gene [1]. It interferes with the normal RARA signalling and blocks myeloid differentiation leading to the accumulation of promyelocytes. This fusion is associated with a form of Acute Promyelocytic Leukaemia which is primarily resistant to the Retinoic Acid treatment [2, 3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1228" y="289" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="USP37" name="Ubiquitin specific peptidase 37" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="E2F1 &amp; !RB1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:20063"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34758854/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34454635/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23208507/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>USP37 node represents the ubiquitin specific peptidase 37 protein [1].
It is a mediator of G1/S transition by protein deubiquitination, and has been associated with oncogenic mechanisms [2, 3].
Its enzymatic activity regulates PLZF::RARA fusion stability [4].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="443" y="309" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="CoAct_COMP" name="Co Activation Complex" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23518351/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17671166/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CoAct_COMP node represents the dynamical assembly of epigenetic enzymes and scaffolding proteins which act on promoter and/or enhancer region thereby activating the transcription of target genes.
Its components include PHF8 [1] and NCOA1 [2].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1054" y="386" style="Epigenetic"/>
    </node>
    <node id="EZH2" name="Enhancer of zeste 2 polycomb repressive complex 2 subunit" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="MYC | GATA2 | (E2F1 &amp; !RB1)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:3527"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21248841/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15362224/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35013218/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35984905/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>EZH2 node represents the enhancer of zeste 2 polycomb repressive complex 2 subunit [1], which is the catalitic subunit of the PRC2 complex, and induces the repressive histone mark H3K27me3 on target genes [2].
It is induced by E2F transcription factors [3].
Evidences point towards a non canonical role of EZH2 in the interaction and stabilization of MYC in cancer [4].
In a PLZF::RARA APL mouse model, the non canonical activity of EZH2 sustains the RA-resistant phenotype [5].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1545" y="632" style="Epigenetic"/>
    </node>
    <node id="PRC2" name="Polycomb repressive complex 2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="EZH2 &amp; CDK2"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21248841/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>PRC2 node represents the Polycomb repressive complex 2 [1].
It is an assembly of different protein subunits, including EED and SUZ1.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1602" y="423" style="Epigenetic"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CoRep_COMP" name="Co-repressive complex" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22406747/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36216898/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9486655/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9765306/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15362224/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35984905/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16449642/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CoRep_COMP node represents the dynamical assembly of epigenetic enzymes and scaffolding proteins, which act on promoter and/or enhancer regions, thereby repressing the transcription of target genes.
Its components include KDM1A [1], NCOR1 [2, 3, 4], PRC1 [5, 6], and SUV39H1 [7].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1044" y="443" style="Epigenetic"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CDKN1A" name="Cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitor 1A" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="((RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !PRC2 &amp; !CoRep_COMP) | CEBPAB | TP53) &amp; !MYC &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
        <exp str="RA &amp; RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
        <exp str="RA:2 &amp; RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !PLZF_RARA"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1784"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12559756/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18024792/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24821728/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24646031/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8940196/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CDKN1A node represents the cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitor 1A, also named p21 [1].
It inhibits the activity of Cyclin/CDK2 and Cyclin/CDK4 complexes [2].
It is repressed by the fusion proteins PML::RARA [3] and PLZF::RARA [4] in APL, and its expression is transactivated in response to RA treatment [5, 6].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="606" y="478" style="Arrest"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CDKN1B" name="Cyclin dependent kinase inhibitor 1B" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!MYC &amp; !SKP2 &amp; !((CCNE2 | CCNA2) &amp; CDK2)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1785"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12559756/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15199159/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CDKN1B node represents the cyclin dependent kinase inhibitor 1B, also named p27 [1].
It inhibits CDK2/Cyclin E2 and CDK2/Cyclin A2 complexes, preventing them from phosphorylating their targets [2].
CDKN1B is phosphorylated by CDK2, and SKP2 promotes the degradation of phosphorylated CDKN1B [3].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="125" y="342" style="Arrest"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CDKN2D" name="Cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitor 2D" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="RA &amp; RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
        <exp str="RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !(CoRep_COMP | PRC2) &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1790"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24412926/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25275592/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19855079/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CDKN2D node represents the cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitor 2D, also named p19 [1].
It prevents the activation of the CDK4 and CDK6 kinases.
It is repressed by both PLML::RARA and PLZF::RARA in leukaemia cells [2, 3, 4].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="752" y="223" style="Arrest"/>
    </node>
    <node id="RB1" name="Retinoblastoma-associated transcriptional corepressor 1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="PML &amp; !PML_RARA &amp; CDKN1B &amp; (!CAK | !(CCND1 &amp; CDK4_6) | !((CCNA2 | CCNE2) &amp; CDK2))"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:9884"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22123859/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11113200/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21205865/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>RB1 node represents the Retinoblastoma-associated transcriptional corepressor 1 [1].
It is a negative regulator of the cell cycle progression [3].
Its activity is regulated by phosphorylation from many Cyclin/CDK complexes [3]. The active, hypophosphorylated form of the protein binds transcription factor E2F1 and represses its targets [4].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="526" y="422" style="Arrest"/>
    </node>
    <node id="TP53" name="Tumor protein p53" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="((PML &amp; !PML_RARA) | MYC) &amp; !(MDM2 | PLZF_RARA)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:11998"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24412926/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24821728/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>TP53  node represents the tumor protein p53 (TP53) [1].
It is repressed by the fusion proteins PML::RARA [3] and PLZF::RARA [2] in APL, and its expression is transactivated in response to RA treatment.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="76" y="752" style="Arrest"/>
    </node>
    <node id="SKP2" name="S-phase kinase associated protein" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="MYC &amp; (PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA | !GATA2)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:10901"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11595732/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34068643/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12393444/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21245140/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>SKP2 node represents the S-phase kinase associated protein 2 [1].
It is an important mediator of S-phase entry.
It is commonly associated with therapy-resistance phenotypes in leukaemic cells [2, 3, 4, 5].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="121" y="209" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="MDM2" name="MDM2 proto-oncogene" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!PML | PML_RARA"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:6973"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15195100/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>MDM2 node represents the MDM2 proto-oncogene [1].
It promotes tumor formation by targeting TP53 for proteasomal degradation.
It is sequestered and inhibited by PML, which favors TP53 stabilization [2].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="151" y="396" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CAK" name="Cyclin-dependent kinase Activating Kinase" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="MYC"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11113200/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16935935/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19917671/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12213824/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CAK node represents the complex named cyclin-dependent kinase (CDK)-activating kinase (CAK), which is a trimeric enzyme complex composed of CDK7, cyclin H and MAT1 [1]. It is involved in the exit of G1 phase and cell cycle progression, by phosphorylating key components of the network, such as CDK4, CDK6, CDK2 and RB1. The RA-induced G1 arrest is associated with a decreased activity of the complex [2, 3, 4].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="377" y="103" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CCNA2" name="Cyclin A2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(MYC | (E2F1 &amp; !RB1)) &amp; (PLZF_RARA | !PLZF)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1578"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22123859/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10023668/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CCNA2 node represents the Cyclin A2 protein, encoded by the CCNA2 gene [1].
It is an important mediator of S-phase entry [2].
It is repressed by PLZF and activated by PLZF::RARA in leukaemia cells [3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="490" y="248" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CCND1" name="Cyclin D1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="MYC | (E2F1 &amp; !RB1)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1582"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22123859/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CCND1 node represents the Cyclin D1 protein encoded by the CCND1 gene [1].
It is an important mediator of G1/S transition in complex with CDK4 or CDK6 [2].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="567" y="576" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CCNE2" name="Cyclin E2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="MYC | (E2F1 &amp; !RB1)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1590"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22123859/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CCNE2 node represents the Cyclin E2 protein, encoded by the CCNE2 gene [1].
It is an important mediator of G1/S transition in complex with CDK2 [2].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="435" y="369" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CDK4_6" name="Cyclin-dependent kinase 4 and 6" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="MYC &amp; (CCND1 | CAK) &amp; !(CDKN2D | CDKN1A)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1773"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1777"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22123859/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11113200/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CDK4_6 node represents both the cyclin-dependent kinase 4 and 6 [1, 2].
These proteins participate in the cell cycle regulation, by mean of their serine/threonine kinase activity [3, 4].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="766" y="532" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CDK2" name="Cyclin-dependent kinase 2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(CCNE2 | CCNA2) &amp; CAK &amp; !(CDKN1A | CDKN1B)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1771"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24646031/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11113200/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CDK2 node represents the cyclin-dependent kinase 2 [3].
It participates in the cell cycle regulation, by mean of its serine/threonine kinase activity [1, 2].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="798" y="344" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="E2F1" name="E2F1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="MYC &amp; (PML_RARA | !(PML &amp; RB1)) &amp; !CDKN1A"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:3113"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15362224/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21205865/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24351540/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35984905/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>E2F1 node represents the E2F transcription factor 1 [1].
It is an important mediator of the cell cycle progression [2].
Its activity is inhibited by PML and RB1 [3, 4].
An E2F transcriptional network was found to be underlying RA resistance in APL mouse model [5].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="217" y="560" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="MYC" name="MYC proto-oncogene" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="E2F1 &amp; !RB1 &amp; EZH2 &amp; (PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA | !PML) &amp; (PLZF_RARA | !PLZF) &amp; !CEBPAB"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:7553"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24704206/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14645547/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19855079/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12869508/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11340171/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35013218/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>MYC node represents the TF encoded by the MYC proto-oncogene [1].
It is an important mediator of cell cycle progression and cellular transformation [2].
It is repressed by PLZF [3], and transactivated by the PLZF::RARA fusion [4].
It is repressed by C/EBPalpha during granulopoiesis [5, 6].
Evidences point towards a non canonical role of EZH2 in the interaction and stabilization of MYC in cancer [7].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="364" y="665" style="Proliferation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="DUSP6" name="Dual specificity phosphatase 6" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!PLZF_RARA &amp; PLZF"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:3072"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19855079/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19723763/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>DUSP6 node represents the dual specificity phosphatase 6 [1].
It negatively regulates MAP-kinases, which are associated with cellular proliferation and differentiation.
It is activated by PLZF and repressed by PLZF::RARA in leukaemia cells [2, 3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1555" y="234" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="POU2F1" name="Oct1 transcription factor" maxvalue="1">
      <parameter val="1"/>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:9212"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16352814/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>POU2F1 node represents the POU class 2 homeobox 1 transcription factor, also named OCT1 [1].
It is required for the SPI1 transactivation [2].
It has a basal value equal to 1.</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1576" y="124" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="GATA2" name="GATA binding protein 2" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="PML &amp; !SPI1"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:4171"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10938104/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>GATA2 node represents the GATA binding protein 2 [1], which is an important mediator involved in the development and proliferation of hematopoietic cells.
The formation of a complex with PML protein potentiates its transactivation capacity [2].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1384" y="439" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="RUNX1" name="RUNX Family Transcription Factor 1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="!PLZF_RARA"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:10471"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19855079/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>RUNX1 node represents the RUNX Family Transcription Factor 1 [1].
It is involved in the development of normal hematopoiesis.
It is repressed by the PLZF::RARA translocation protein [2].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1550" y="305" style=""/>
    </node>
    <node id="SPI1" name="SPI1" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="(SPI1 | CEBPAB) &amp; POU2F1 &amp; PLZF &amp; !GATA2 &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
        <exp str="RA &amp; RARA &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:11241"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20159610/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16352814/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22105598/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>SPI1 node represents the protein encoded by the Spi-1 proto-oncogene, also named PU1 [1], which is an important mediator of myeloid differentiation.
SPI1 activity is repressed by PML::RARA and PLZF::RARA fusion proteins in APL [2, 3, 4].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1327" y="704" style="Differentiation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CEBPAB" name="C/EBPalpha and C/EBPbeta" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="RA &amp; RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
        <exp str="(SPI1 | (RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !CoRep_COMP &amp; !PRC2)) &amp; !PLZF &amp; !(PLZF_RARA | PML_RARA)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1833"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1834"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14592978/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32393309/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23898169/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20159610/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19723763/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CEBPAB node represents both the C/EBPalpha and C/EBPbeta proteins [1, 2], which are important mediators of myeloid differentiation.
C/EBPalpha activity is repressed by PML::RARA and PLZF::RARA fusion proteins in APL [3, 4, 5, 6].
</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="1150" y="797" style="Differentiation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="CEBPE" name="C/EBPepsilon" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="SPI1 &amp; PML &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA | CoRep_COMP)"/>
        <exp str="RA &amp; SPI1 &amp; PML &amp; RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
        <exp str="RA:2 &amp; SPI1 &amp; PML &amp; RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !PLZF_RARA"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:1836"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17562868/"/>
          <link xlink:href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19855079/"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>CEBPE node represents the C/EBPepsilon protein [1], which is an important mediator of myeloid differentiation.
C/EBPepsilon is target of repression by PML::RARA and PLZF::RARA fusion proteins in APL [2, 3].</comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="977" y="563" style="Differentiation"/>
    </node>
    <node id="RARB" name="Retinoic acid receptor beta" maxvalue="1">
      <value val="1">
        <exp str="RA &amp; RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
        <exp str="RARA &amp; CoAct_COMP &amp; !(CoRep_COMP | PRC2) &amp; !(PML_RARA | PLZF_RARA)"/>
      </value>
      <annotation>
        <linklist>
          <link xlink:href="https://www.genenames.org/data/gene-symbol-report/#!/hgnc_id/HGNC:9865"/>
        </linklist>
        <comment>RARB node represents the retinoic acid receptor beta [1].
It binds retinoic acid which mediates terminal myeloid differentiation. </comment>
      </annotation>
      <nodevisualsetting x="902" y="831" style="Differentiation"/>
    </node>
