      </linklist>
      <comment>Predictive modelling of Acute Promyelocytic Leukaemia resistance to Retinoic Acid therapy.

Authors: José A. Sánchez-Villanueva (1), Lia N’Guyen (2), Mathilde Poplineau (2), Estelle Duprez (2), Élisabeth Remy (1) &amp; Denis Thieffry (3,4)

1) Aix Marseille Univ, CNRS, I2M, Marseille, France.
2) Integrative molecular biology in hematopoiesis and leukemia, Equipe Labellisée Ligue Contre le Cancer, CRCM, Inserm UMR1068, CNRS UMR7258, Institut Paoli-Calmettes, Aix Marseille Univ, Marseille, France.
3) Department of Biology, École Normale Supérieure, Paris, France.
4) Institut Curie - INSERM U900 - Mines Paris, PSL Research University, Paris, France.

This model was designed to study the main features of resistance to Retinoic Acid (RA) treatment applied to Acute Promyelocytic Leukemia (APL) cells [1, 2, 3].
Briefly, acute Promyelocytic Leukaemia (APL) results from an aberrant chromosomal translocation involving the Retinoic Acid Receptor Alpha (RARA) gene, most frequently with the Promyelocytic Leukaemia (PML) or Promyelocytic Leukaemia Zinc Finger (PLZF) gene. These oncoproteins block the normal haematopoietic differentiation program and promote aberrant proliferative promyelocytes.

A differentiation therapy based on high doses of Retinoic Acid (RA) is successful in most of the PML::RARA patients, while PLZF::RARA patients frequently display treatment resistance and relapse.

Previously published computational models [4, 5, 6, 7] focused on haematopoietic specification processes  were used for the model construction. The resulting model integrates signalling, transcriptional and epigenetic regulatory mechanisms, thereby capturing the key  activities of the two fusion proteins, as well as of their wild type counterpart, which underly cell responses to physiological and pharmacological RA treatments.

More specifically, an analysis of single cell omics data (RNAseq and ATACseq data) for RA-treated versus control cells from an APL mouse model expressing the PLZF::RARA translocation revealed a potential role for EZH2 non canonical epigenetic activity sustaining RA-resistance [8], which could be assessed using this model.

The stable states of the model recapitulate the main phenotypes of the APL subtypes and their different responses to RA.</comment>
    </annotation>
